<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-439-685  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 439 685.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Sept 21 1990 n1516* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>UK Industry Department three-year open systems promotion budgetspent in 15 months. (UK Department of Trade and Industry's OpenSystems Technology Transfer program)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Great Britain. Department of Trade and IndustryBudgetingOpen SystemsGovernment FundingStandardization.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>UK INDUSTRY DEPARTMENT THREE-YEAR OPEN SYSTEMS PROMOTIONandM;BUDGET SPENT IN 15 MONTHSandM;The UK Department of Trade and Industry is now 15 months into its three-yearOpen Systems Technology Transfer programme, and has already spent the #12.7moriginally allocated for the project.andP;  It has produced a wealth of brochuresand pamphlets encouraging businesses and organisations to begin adopting opensystems strategies in their information technology plans, however there islittle of any substance.andP;  The Department refuses to deal in specifics, andalthough it says it has identified international standards that may be worthsupporting in the areas of graphical user interfaces, data structures,distributed applications and operating system functions - it does not saywhat those standards are, although a positioning statement is beingprepared.andO;At a briefing in London last week,Department officials revealed that fouropen systems demonstration projects are now up and running at AstonUniversity, Northamptonshire Health Authority, Rolls Royce and Lucas DieselSystems.andP;  A spokesman described systems interconnction and applicationsportability as &quot;key areas of interest&quot; - presumed to be muted references toOSI and X/Open's Common Application Environment - but went on to say that theDepartment is &quot;trying to tell people open systems isn't just about OSI andUnix&quot;, that the relevance of X/Open's standards effort &quot;is a subject open fordebate,&quot; and that &quot;Unix is a proprietary system&quot;.andP;  Perhaps the whole thing isbest summed up by the opening comments of the briefing - &quot;there is not enoughsound and practical advice to help users make up their minds.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>